\fs36 \cf2 The fallible character of human knowledge\
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sl480\sa240

\fs24 \cf2 As the previous module should have convinced you, there is no infallible route to truth in science. In the face of apparently falsifying evidence, a scientist can always propose to reject another assumption or to fault the experimental procedure that produced the evidence. Sometimes it is entirely reasonable for a scientist to simply recognize that a certain bit of evidence does seem to count against his or her hypothesis, and leave the problem for future generations. Moreover, a highly confirmed theory supported by many correct predictions can eventually be rejected as either new evidence arises which falsifies them or as new alternative plausible hypotheses emerge that equally explain the same phenomena.\
One response to realizing that science is not so clear cut is skepticism \'97 deny that we can never know the truth about the world and give up the quest to try to know. This response, however, seems extreme given the manifest success of science in revealing a great deal about the operation of the world. Even if some of what scientists claim to know now turns out to be false, it is highly unlikely that all the claims of modern science will turn out to be radically mistaken. A more plausible response is\'a0
\i fallibilism
\i0 . This recognizes that any of the claims to knowledge at a time might later be withdrawn as counter evidence or better hypotheses are developed, but also that overall the hypotheses of today are a major advance of those of a previous era. To gain an appreciation for the fallible character of science, consider two examples from the history of science, one of a theory that seemed well ensconced until it tumbled quickly at the end of the 18th century, and another which experienced ups and downs over two centuries before finally giving way.\cell \lastrow\row
